by Lreus at 2018-10-08T19:11:43Z

@javiereguiluz
Hello javiereguiluz I am glad if I can be of any help and i hope i won't make you waste your time.

Indeed since i use PhpUnit in my job's Symfony project the command phpunit isn't available in the project bin directory after a  `composer require --dev symfony/phpunit-bridge` as mentionned at [https://symfony.com/doc/current/testing.html](url) .
It seems logic as `ls -al ./bin` command only mention the "console" file

In fact, the TestCase class  is not even available before i launch `./vendor/bin/simple-phpunit` as it installs some composer requirements

I checked my original composer.json and it contains symfony/flex:^1.0 in its require section.
If you need i think i may be able to provide you a version cleaned from our specific project repositories

The answer in those links worked and made me think the documentation was outdated (Let me apologize if it not the case)
 [https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47902541/symfony-how-to-correctly-switch-from-phpunit-phpunit-to-phpunit-bridge?rq=1](url)
[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47569173/how-to-configure-phpstorm-to-use-symfony-phpunit-bridge](url)

Edit:
I used your hints to ask for some help with a senior developper i am working with.
It appears that we require symfony/phpunit-bridge in our project's composer.json file and that would make composer to not execute the symfony recipes on the first `composer install`.

It seems that two solutions were available:

- Removing the symfony.lock file after the git clone command allowed to execute the recipes after the first `composer install` and the file ./bin/phpunit was created.

- If the project was already started removing and requiring again the bundle symfony/phpunit-bridge allowed to execute the recipes and created the command ./bin/phpunit

Could it be usefull to write that if the command is missing the recipes may have not been executed ?

